In a press briefing, White House Press Secretary Jen Psaki announced that the US has evacuated over 37,000 people from Afghanistan since August 14th. This includes American citizens, third-country nationals, Afghan allies, and Afghans at risk of persecution. Psaki also stated that 28 US military flights and 61 coalition aircraft have evacuated approximately 16,000 people in the last 24 hours alone. She emphasized that the evacuation operation is complex and dangerous, but the US remains committed to bringing its people and Afghan partners home. Psaki also addressed concerns about the Taliban's red line on the August 31st deadline and stated that the US is in talks with the Taliban on a daily basis. She mentioned that the President will make a decision on extending the deadline based on the progress of the evacuation operation. Psaki also discussed the upcoming G7 Leaders Meeting on Afghanistan and the administration's efforts to address the humanitarian needs of the Afghan people. Additionally, she mentioned that the FDA's full approval of the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine could encourage more Americans to get vaccinated. Finally, Psaki acknowledged the challenges and criticisms the President is facing in the handling of the Afghanistan crisis, but emphasized his commitment to making decisions in the best interest of national security and the American people.